Data cleaning¶

In [9]:
def preprocess_data1(data):
    # Make a copy of the original dataset to avoid modifying the input data
    preprocessed_data = data.copy()

    # Replace any white spaces in column names with underscores
    preprocessed_data.columns = [col.replace(" ", "_") for col in preprocessed_data.columns]

    # Modify the date columns
    for col in preprocessed_data.columns:
        if "date" in col.lower():
            preprocessed_data[col] = preprocessed_data[col].apply(custom_date_parser)
            preprocessed_data[col] = pd.to_datetime(preprocessed_data[col])

    # Remove the $ sign from any columns containing it
    for col in preprocessed_data.columns:
        if preprocessed_data[col].dtype == 'object':
            preprocessed_data[col] = preprocessed_data[col].str.replace('$', '')

    # Remove any white spaces in the data
    preprocessed_data = preprocessed_data.applymap(lambda x: x.strip() if isinstance(x, str) else x)

    # Remove the suffix CT in the CAG_Count_Value column
    preprocessed_data['CAG_Count_Value'] = preprocessed_data['CAG_Count_Value'].str.replace('CT', '')

    # Remove the suffix OZ in the CAG_Ounces_Value column
    preprocessed_data['CAG_Ounces_Value'] = preprocessed_data['CAG_Ounces_Value'].str.replace('OZ', '')

    return preprocessed_data

def custom_date_parser(date_string):
    return pd.to_datetime(date_string, format='Week Ending %m-%d-%y')

def preprocess_data2(data):
    # Make a copy of the original dataset to avoid modifying the input data
    preprocessed_data = data.copy()

    # Replace any white spaces in column names with underscores
    preprocessed_data.columns = [col.replace(" ", "_") for col in preprocessed_data.columns]

    # Modify the Time column
    preprocessed_data['Time'] = preprocessed_data['Time'].apply(custom_date_parser)

    # Extract features from the Time column
    preprocessed_data['Year'] = preprocessed_data['Time'].dt.year
    preprocessed_data['Month'] = preprocessed_data['Time'].dt.month # while using refer to year also or if checking for a particular month like december
    preprocessed_data['Week_Number'] = preprocessed_data['Time'].dt.isocalendar().week # only in timeseries 
    #preprocessed_data['Day_of_Week'] = preprocessed_data['Time'].dt.dayofweek # not required

    # Sort the data by Time column
    preprocessed_data.sort_values('Time', inplace=True)

    # Create a new column with consecutive week numbers
    preprocessed_data['Week_Number_Consecutive'] = preprocessed_data.groupby('Time').cumcount() + 1

    # Additional cleaning and preprocessing steps can be added here, depending on the specific dataset

    return preprocessed_data

# Create new columns with the log of the specified columns
IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Salads'] = np.log(IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Salads'])
# IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Salads'] = np.log(IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Salads'])
# IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Sprays'] = np.log(IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Sprays'])
IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Sprays'] = np.log(IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Sprays'])
IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Salads'] = np.log(IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Price_per_unit_Cooking_Salads'])
IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Sprays'] = np.log(IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Price_per_unit_Cooking_Sprays'])

# IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Salads * log_Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Sprays'] = IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Salads']*IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Dollar_Sales_Cooking_Sprays']
IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Salads * log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Sprays'] = IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Salads']*IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Sprays']
IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Salads * log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Sprays'] = IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Salads']*IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Sprays']


x = IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2[[
    'log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Salads','log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Sprays','log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Sprays',
    'log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Salads',
    'log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Salads * log_Total_Unit_Sales_Cooking_Sprays','log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Salads * log_Price_per_unit_Cooking_Sprays']
    ]
y = IRI_POS_Tablespreads_Q2['Total_Unit_Sales_x'].tolist()
y = [math.log(i) for i in y]

# adding the constant term

x = sm.add_constant(x)

# performing the regression
# and fitting the model

result = sm.OLS(y, x).fit()

# printing the summary table

print(result.summary())

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Define the range of n_estimators
n_estimators_range = list(range(1, 101, 5))

# Initialize lists to store training and validation errors
training_errors = []
validation_errors = []

# Iterate over the range of n_estimators
for n_estimators in n_estimators_range:
    # Fit the RandomForestRegressor model with the current n_estimators value
    model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n_estimators, random_state=42)
    model.fit(X_CNG_train, y_CNG_train)

    # Calculate the training error
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_CNG_train)
    train_error = mean_squared_error(y_CNG_train, y_train_pred)
    training_errors.append(train_error)

    # Calculate the validation error
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_CNG_val)
    val_error = mean_squared_error(y_CNG_val, y_val_pred)
    validation_errors.append(val_error)

# Plot the training and validation errors against the model complexity
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(n_estimators_range, training_errors, label='Training Error')
plt.plot(n_estimators_range, validation_errors, label='Validation Error')
plt.xlabel('Number of Trees (n_estimators)')
plt.ylabel('Mean Squared Error')
plt.title('Bias-Variance Trade-Off')
plt.legend()

# Display the plot
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get the individual tree predictions
def get_tree_predictions(model, X):
    tree_predictions = np.array([tree.predict(X) for tree in model.estimators_])
    return tree_predictions

# Calculate the prediction intervals
def calculate_prediction_intervals(tree_predictions, X, percentile=95):
    lower_percentile = (100 - percentile) / 2
    upper_percentile = 100 - lower_percentile
    lower_bounds = np.percentile(tree_predictions, lower_percentile, axis=0)
    upper_bounds = np.percentile(tree_predictions, upper_percentile, axis=0)
    return lower_bounds, upper_bounds

# Fit the RandomForestRegressor model
model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_CNG_train, y_CNG_train)

# Get the individual tree predictions for the test set
tree_predictions = get_tree_predictions(model, X_CNG_test)

# Calculate the 95% prediction intervals
lower_bounds, upper_bounds = calculate_prediction_intervals(tree_predictions, X_CNG_test, percentile=95)

# Plot the prediction intervals and actual observations
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(y_CNG_test.index, y_CNG_test, 'o', label='Actual Observations')
plt.plot(y_CNG_test.index, lower_bounds, 'r--', label='Lower Bound (95% Confidence)')
plt.plot(y_CNG_test.index, upper_bounds, 'r--', label='Upper Bound (95% Confidence)')
plt.fill_between(y_CNG_test.index, lower_bounds, upper_bounds, color='red', alpha=0.1)
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Target Variable')
plt.title('Prediction Intervals for RandomForestRegressor')
plt.legend()

# Display the plot
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from mlxtend.feature_selection import SequentialFeatureSelector

# Instantiate a LinearRegression model
linear_regression = LinearRegression()

# Forward stepwise selection
forward_selector = SequentialFeatureSelector(
    linear_regression, k_features="best", forward=True, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=5
)

# Fit the forward selector on the training data
forward_selector.fit(X_CNG_train, y_CNG_train)

# Get the selected features
selected_features_forward = X_CNG_train.columns[list(forward_selector.k_feature_idx_)]

# Backward stepwise selection
backward_selector = SequentialFeatureSelector(
    linear_regression, k_features="best", forward=False, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=5
)

# Fit the backward selector on the training data
backward_selector.fit(X_CNG_train, y_CNG_train)

# Get the selected features
selected_features_backward = X_CNG_train.columns[list(backward_selector.k_feature_idx_)]

# Print the selected features
print("Selected features (forward stepwise selection):")
print(selected_features_forward)

print("Selected features (backward stepwise selection):")
print(selected_features_backward)
